title: Add Callback Manager (for realsies this time)
body:
This is the current state of my attempt to add a callback manager within llama index. 

Mainly all that's left is to decide if we are sending too much or not enough info through the callbacks. I had some ideas for adding query, retrieve, and synthesize events but they were either redundant or I couldn't find a good place to insert them 🤔 

Extremely open to changes!

Todo:
- [x] base callback handler
- [x] base callback manager
- [x] llama debugger handler
- [x] add callback manager to service context
- [x] Insert callback hooks by following the service context around
- [x] Probably refactor the inputs to on_start and on_end (make it less verbose? not sure yet)
- [ ] evaluate if more or less data is needed to be logged
- [x] linting
- [x] tests


Example Usage:
```python
>>> from gpt_index.callbacks.base import CallbackManager
>>> from gpt_index.callbacks.llama_debug import LlamaDebugHandler
>>> from gpt_index import SimpleDirectoryReader, GPTVectorStoreIndex, ServiceContext
>>> from gpt_index.callbacks.schema import CBEventType
>>>
>>> llama_debug_handler = LlamaDebugHandler()
>>> callback_manager = CallbackManager([llama_debug_handler])
>>> service_context = ServiceContext.from_defaults(callback_manager=callback_manager)
>>>
>>> docs = SimpleDirectoryReader("./data").load_data()
>>> index = GPTVectorStoreIndex.from_documents(docs, service_context=service_context)

INFO:gpt_index.token_counter.token_counter:> [build_index_from_nodes] Total embedding token usage: 17617 tokens
>>> llama_debug_handler.events[CBEventType.EMBEDDING]
[CBEvent(event_type=<CBEventType.EMBEDDING: 'embedding'>, 
              payload=None, 
              time='04/27/2023, 22:24:37', 
              id='7d6b3caf-c9a4-4172-a9a9-033a43d441de'), 
 CBEvent(event_type=<CBEventType.EMBEDDING: 'embedding'>,

              time='04/27/2023, 22:24:38', 
              id='7d6b3caf-c9a4-4172-a9a9-033a43d441de')
```

title: Fixed an issue where document inserts would not also set the doc_hash after insert
body:
This is a bug that has a downstream effect of affecting refreshes. During a refresh, the code checks to see if the doc_hash of the updated document matches the doc_hash of the doc stored in the index. This was not being set during insert.

This has fixed the refresh issue in my code. Now, I don't get stuck in refresh loops.

title: added image caption parsers and ipynb parser
body:
hi, thanks for the cool repo

I added some file parsers that I made for myself, I thought they'd be useful to share.

I added 3 parser classes:
- ImageCaptionParser: Uses an image captioning model (Blip)
- ImageVisionLLMParser: Uses Blip2 which acts similarly to GPT4
- IPYNBParser: jupyter notebook parser (converts it into a markdown/python file, all markdown cells become comments

you can test them by running something like this:

```python
reader = SimpleDirectoryReader(
    input_files=["demo.jpg"],
    file_extractor={
        ".jpg": gpt_index.readers.file.base.ImageCaptionParser(),
    }
)
documents = reader.load_data()
```

I tried to follow your same convention, excuse me if there are some discrepancies

I noticed that there's an ImageParser class which uses Donut to read text from files, which is great but sometimes I want the actual content of the image, thus I added 2

title: 🌟 MyScale VectorStore Support to LlamaIndex
body:
# [MyScale](https://myscale.com) Vector Store

MyScale is a high-performance SQL + Vector OLAP database built on ClickHouse.  You can find more details on [MyScale's website](https://myscale.com)

## 📚 How to use

1. Go to [MyScale](https://myscale.com) and click on sign up.
2. Go to your console to [create a cluster](https://docs.myscale.com/en/cluster-management/)
3. Get your `Connection Details` under `Action` column under cluster table.
4. Create a MyScale Client with your connection details

```python
import clickhouse_connect
from gpt_index import GPTMyScaleIndex, SimpleDirectoryReader

# Creating a MyScale client
client = clickhouse_connect.get_client(
    host='YOUR_CLUSTER_HOST', 
    port=8443, 
    username='YOUR_USERNAME', 
    password='YOUR_CLUSTER_PASSWORD'
)

# Load documents, build the GPTMyScaleIndex
index = GPTMyScaleIndex.from_documents(documents, myscale_client=client)
```

## ❓What to expect
MyScale is designed for storage and analysis for massive vector data with structured metadatas. If you are eager to find a high performance vector search using SQL queries, [MyScale](https://docs.myscale.com/en/vector-reference/) may be your preferred option. 
Thanks to the advantages of native structural database support, it provides you **a flexible filter** with `WHERE` clause in reader, even `JOIN` when you want to jointly search vectors with filters on relevant metadata from other tables.  `WHERE` clause is supported in `MyScaleReader`.

And it is also open for register and offers free-tier plan for you!

## 🔍 Other Apps

[HuggingFace demos](https://huggingface.co/myscale) are also available if you are curious about its realtime performance.

P.S.: If you are interested in the super secret recipe on building high performance AI+DB applications with MyScale, please visit [here](https://docs.myscale.com/en/advanced-applications/)

title: [0.6.0] Refactor index
body:
### Summary
* Refactor monolithic index class into 3 layers: 
  1. index (manages state, construction, and update), 
  2. retriever (exposes node retrieval interface)
  3. query engine (exposes query interface)
* Original high-level interface remains as
```
index = GPTSimpleVectorIndex.from_documents(...)
query_engine = index.as_query_engine(...)
response = query_engine.query(...)
```
### Additional Details
* Replace query combiner construct with `MultiStepQueryEngine`
* Replace query runner construct with `ComposableGraphQueryEngine`

### Todos
- [x] Update unit tests
- [x] Fix lint
- [x] Spot check notebooks
- [x] Update documentation

title: [Draft] Initial commit of Redis Vector Store
body:
## Description

Draft PR of the Redis Vector Store for LLamaIndex. Overall this is a fairly quick implementation so there is still much to do, however I was able to get the basic doc readers and some of the other examples working fairly easily.

## Questions for team

1. How do you want imports handled? Seemingly different across vector stores. Import on initialization? 
2. ``extras_require`` in requirements.txt?
3.  I saw milvus included password in the ``config_dict`` method, but I don't love that... better practices?
4. Assuming we should create index on command if not created when documents are added?
5. I don't quite understand how I'm supposed to use ``DocumentRelationship``. Pointers?
6. Would y'all be ok with a ``redis_utils`` folder for a bit of cleanup and nicer imports?

Overall, I should be able to clean up and do the rest of the following by this week or next. 

TODO
- [ ] Hybrid queries
- [ ] Fix document relationship
- [ ] Return similarities
- [ ] Better connection handling
- [ ] fix importing 
- [ ] Code clean up and comments
- [ ] Tests
- [ ] Example

Future PRs
